04224nam a22005175i 9780226433349DE-B159720191022022751.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191022s2018    ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802264333497 a10.7208/97802264333492doi  a(DE-B1597)524340  a(OCoLC)1028188867  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aJZ1249 7aPOL0000002bisacsh04a327.11 aGilady, Lilach, eauthor.14aThe Price of Prestige :bConspicuous Consumption in International Relations /cLilach Gilady. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tChapter 1. Explaining Conspicuous Consumption in International Relations -- tChapter 2. Status Symbols and Luxury Goods in International Relations -- tChapter 3. The Aircraft Carrier Club -- tChapter 4. A Contest of Beneficence: Prosociality in International Relations -- tChapter 5. Big Science and the Transits of Venus: The First Race to Space -- tChapter 6. Conclusions: Living in a Veblenian World -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIf wars are costly and risky to both sides, why do they occur? Why engage in an arms race when it's clear that increasing one's own defense expenditures will only trigger a similar reaction by the other side, leaving both countries just as insecure-and considerably poorer? Just as people buy expensive things precisely because they are more expensive, because they offer the possibility of improved social status or prestige, so too do countries, argues Lilach Gilady.             In The Price of Prestige, Gilady shows how many seemingly wasteful government expenditures that appear to contradict the laws of demand actually follow the pattern for what are known as Veblen goods, or positional goods for which demand increases alongside price, even when cheaper substitutes are readily available. From flashy space programs to costly weapons systems a country does not need and cannot maintain to foreign aid programs that offer little benefit to recipients, these conspicuous and strategically timed expenditures are intended to instill awe in the observer through their wasteful might. And underestimating the important social role of excess has serious policy implications. Increasing the cost of war, for example, may not always be an effective tool for preventing it, Gilady argues, nor does decreasing the cost of weapons and other technologies of war necessarily increase the potential for conflict, as shown by the case of a cheap fighter plane whose price tag drove consumers away. In today's changing world, where there are high levels of uncertainty about the distribution of power, Gilady also offers a valuable way to predict which countries are most likely to be concerned about their position and therefore adopt costly, excessive policies.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aInternational relations - Economic aspects. 0aInternational relationsxEconomic aspects. 0aInternational relationsxSocial aspects. 0aPrestige. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226433349423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/doc/cover/9780226433349.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles